  "prompt": "How do conjugations in Greek, Latin and Sanskrit compare to each other?",
  "response": "Conjugations in Greek, Latin, and Sanskrit share some similarities due to their Indo-European language roots, but also have distinct characteristics:\n\nSimilarities:\n- All three languages have complex verb conjugation systems\n- They use inflectional morphology to indicate:\n  - Tense\n  - Mood\n  - Person\n  - Number\n- They have synthetic verb forms (changes within the verb itself)\n\nGreek:\n- Highly inflected verb system\n- Uses different stem variations\n- Has aspectual distinctions (perfective/imperfective)\n- Three main verb voices: active, middle, passive\n- Complex system of moods (indicative, subjunctive, optative, imperative)\n\nLatin:\n- Four main conjugation classes\n- Strong emphasis on regular verb endings\n- Less complex aspectual system compared to Greek\n- Active and passive voices\n- Similar mood system to Greek\n\nSanskrit:\n- Most complex conjugation system of the three\n- Extensive use of sandhi (phonetic modifications)\n- Ten verb classes with distinct conjugation patterns\n- Elaborate system of participles\n- More verb stems and variations\n- Strong focus on root transformations\n\nAll three languages demonstrate the rich morphological complexity characteristic of classical Indo-European languages.",
